 from ending the judge’s legal investments, it manifested an intensification of engagement with the law in the attempt to prove that becoming a woman did not deprive the judge of legal competence. Schreber’s experience of bodily change and his account of interior life has been the subject of more than a century of psychoanalytic and medical scrutiny. With the contemporary trans turn, interest in the judge’s desire to become a woman has intensified. In Laws of Transgression, Peter Goodrich, Katrin Trüstedt, and contributing authors set out to unfold Schreber’s complex relation to the law. The collection revisits and rediscovers the Memoirs, not only in its juridical and political implications, but as a transgressional text that has challenged law and heteronormativity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aJudgeszGermanyvBiography. 0aJudgeszGermanyy19th centuryvBiography. 0aJurisprudencezGermany. 0aLawzGermany. 0aTransgender womenzGermanyvBiography. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aJudge Schreber.  aclinic and critique.  alaw and gender.  alaw and psychoanalysis.  apsychotheology.  aqueer legal theory.  atransgender.1 aGandorfer, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGephart, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGherovici, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodrich, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodrich, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMitchell, W.J.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaikumar, Rajgopal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanders, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmitz,